<include>context/python_preamble.prompt</include>

% Goal
Write the `pdd/context_audit.py` module.

% Role & Scope
Own the deterministic, LLM-free context-audit business logic that was previously embedded in the `pdd context` Click command (PR #1387 review #2). The module preprocesses a prompt the same way generation's first pass does and reports how many tokens each source segment (prompt body, each `<include>`, grounding, …) contributes to the hydrated payload, returning a structured result. It is presentation-free (no Click, no rendering) and applies no budget policy — it reports facts; callers decide rendering and any threshold exit behavior. Both the `pdd context` CLI and the `pdd connect` server endpoint import this one core so they always give identical answers.

% Requirements
1. Define two frozen dataclasses as the structured result:
   - `AuditRow` with fields `source: str`, `tokens: int`, `status` (one of `"resolved"`, `"unresolved"`, `"deferred"`, `"unavailable"`, `"body"`), and `note: Optional[str] = None`. Do NOT store a percent on the row — percent is a presentation concern computed by callers against a chosen basis.
   - `ContextAudit` with fields `model: str`, `total_tokens: int`, `context_limit: Optional[int]`, `percent_used: Optional[float]`, `rows: List[AuditRow]`, `warnings: List[str]`.
   - Each row's `status` classifies it so agent/code callers never have to parse human warning strings: `resolved` (an include whose realized content was hydrated and counted), `unresolved` (a top-level include path that does not resolve to a file), `deferred` (nondeterministic markup — `<shell>`/`<web>`/`query=` includes, `${VAR}` include-many lists), `unavailable` (a known segment requiring PDD Cloud — grounding), `body` (the prompt body).
2. Hydrate deterministically (pass 1) exactly as generation's first preprocessing pass does: call `preprocess(text, recursive=True, double_curly_brackets=False, snapshot_recorder=...)` to obtain the hydrated text. Make NO LLM call, run NO shell, fetch NO web. Attribution MUST be derived from this real expansion (so include selectors are honored), never by re-reading whole include files.
3. Capture per-include attribution from the expansion itself via an in-memory `snapshot_recorder` whose `record_include` accepts preprocess's keyword contract (`source_path`, `content`, `query=None`, `output=None`, and a trailing catch-all that includes `include_depth`). Record each resolved include's *realized* content (already narrowed by `lines=`/`select=`/`mode=`/compression, with nested includes expanded). Ignore records whose `query` is set (LLM-driven, handled as deferred). Other `record_*` hooks are no-ops.
4. Count tokens of each include's realized content — NOT the whole file — using `count_tokens` from `pdd.server.token_counter`. A nested include is expanded into its parent, so keep only records at include depth 0 (the directives the user authored), summing repeated includes of the same source. Independent top-level includes must both appear even when one file's realized content is a substring of another's.
5. `<include-many>` is deferred past the recursive pass; expand literal (non-`${VAR}`) top-level `<include-many>` lists deterministically via `process_include_many_tags` (passing the same recorder) so each listed file is attributed and counted. Respect code-span handling: `<include-many>` syntax inside fenced/inline code is documentation, not a directive (use `_extract_code_spans`/`_intersects_any_span` from `pdd.preprocess`). For variable-driven (`${...}`) lists, record a deferred warning and do not bill their markup as payload.
6. Detect deferred dynamic tags (`<shell>`, `<web>`, and semantic `query=` includes) in the **expanded** payload (not just the raw prompt) so tags inside included files are caught. Detection MUST be code-span aware: dynamic syntax inside fenced or inline code is literal documentation and must NOT be warned on, stripped, or counted. Implement this locally with regex patterns plus the `_extract_code_spans`/`_intersects_any_span` span check (do not rely on `context_snapshot.detect_dynamic_tags`, which is not span-aware). Emit one warning per detected tag and also add a zero-token `deferred` `AuditRow` for it.
7. Exclude unexpanded dynamic-tag markup from the deterministic total: strip `<shell>…</shell>`, `<web>…</web>`, and `query=` includes (only outside code spans) before counting, so deferred markup is never billed as hydrated payload. The `total_tokens` is the token count of the strip-then-hydrated payload.
8. Surface unresolved/missing includes: any top-level `<include>`/`<include-many>` path the real preprocess path would act on that does not resolve to a readable file (excluding `${VAR}` paths, which are deferred) MUST appear both as a warning and as a `0`-token row with `status="unresolved"`. Reuse preprocess's code-span-aware and optional-aware behavior: include syntax inside code fences/inline code must not warn or count, and optional missing includes must be skipped silently. Before running the deterministic include processors for this check, strip semantic `query=`-only includes so preprocess's `IncludeQueryExtractor` (a real LLM call) is never reached.
9. Never trigger semantic `query=` extraction during the audit. Set `PDD_QUIET=1` and `PDD_CONTEXT_AUDIT_NO_QUERY_FALLBACK=1` for the duration of hydration and unresolved detection (restoring prior values afterward) so preprocess never falls back to `IncludeQueryExtractor` when a deterministic `select=` on a `query=` include fails; the deferred query include is still surfaced via the dynamic-tag warning/row.
10. Build rows in this order, then sort by `tokens` descending: one `resolved` row per top-level include/include-many file (label by path relative to cwd when possible); `unresolved` rows; `deferred` rows; a `prompt_body` row whose tokens are the deterministic total minus the attributed includes, clamped at zero (tokenizer boundary effects can make the subtraction slightly negative); and a `grounding` row with `0` tokens, `status="unavailable"`, and a `"unavailable (requires cloud)"` note (no network call).
11. `audit_prompt_text(text, model, *, base_dir=None)` runs the audit on already-loaded text; when `base_dir` is given, resolve relative includes from that directory (so the server can match a CLI run from a project root) by temporarily changing the working directory. It computes `context_limit` via `get_context_limit(model)` and `percent_used` via `percent(total_tokens, context_limit)`, returning a `ContextAudit`. `audit_prompt_file(prompt_path, model, *, base_dir=None)` reads the file as UTF-8 and delegates to `audit_prompt_text`, forwarding `base_dir` so the server can pass a project root instead of changing cwd in its route handler.
12. Provide pure helpers: `percent(part, whole)` returns `round(part/whole*100, 1)` or `None` when `whole` is falsy; `row_percent(row, total_tokens)` returns `percent(row.tokens, total_tokens) or 0.0`; `threshold_exceeded(percent_used, threshold)` returns `True` only when `percent_used is not None and 0 < threshold < percent_used` (so `threshold == 0` disables it). The core itself never enforces a budget or exits.
13. Redirect stdout to an in-memory buffer around the preprocess/include-processor calls so their progress lines cannot corrupt a caller's machine-readable output.
14. Import token utilities from `pdd.server.token_counter` (`count_tokens`, `get_context_limit`) and preprocessing utilities from `pdd.preprocess` (`preprocess`, `process_backtick_includes`, `process_include_tags`, `process_include_many_tags`, `compute_user_intent_paths`, `_extract_code_spans`, `_intersects_any_span`, `_parse_attrs`), and the path resolver from `pdd.path_resolution` (`get_default_resolver`). Keep `count_tokens` and `get_context_limit` as module globals so tests can monkeypatch them. Import only leaf libraries — never `pdd.commands.*` or `pdd.server.routes.*` — to avoid import cycles.
15. Do not require an LLM call for any portion of the audit.
16. Serialize the process-global cwd/env mutation. The env-var setting (req. 9) and the `base_dir` working-directory change (req. 11) mutate *process-global* state, and under `pdd connect` the server calls this audit from a request handler while the connect prompt screen fires it alongside `/analyze` in one debounced cycle — two cwd-sensitive operations in flight at once. Guard the entire env+cwd set-yield-restore window with a module-level reentrant lock (`threading.RLock`) so concurrent audits (and any other server work that opts in) can never observe a half-applied cwd and resolve includes against the wrong directory (PR #1387 review #3). Export a public `cwd_env_lock()` context manager that holds this same lock, so cwd-sensitive callers outside this module — notably the `/analyze` route, which does its own `chdir` + `preprocess` — can serialize against the audit. The lock MUST be reentrant so a caller already holding it via `cwd_env_lock()` that then runs an audit does not deadlock.

% Deliverables
- Code: `pdd/context_audit.py`
